Perfect! Now I can see the issue clearly. The native implementation (which handles iOS targets) does NOT have the special case for `ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET` format. Instead, it uses the generic format parsing on line 140-144:

```kotlin
public actual fun parse(input: CharSequence, format: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents>): Instant = try {
    format.parse(input).toInstantUsingOffset()
} catch (e: IllegalArgumentException) {
    throw DateTimeFormatException("Failed to parse an instant from '$input'", e)
}
```

This means native platforms (including iOS) use the actual kotlinx-datetime format definition of `ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET`, which requires the seconds field to be present (line 103-124 in DateTimeComponents.kt).

But JVM and CommonJs have special cases that delegate to platform-specific implementations (`jtOffsetDateTime.parse()`), which are more lenient and allow omitting seconds.

The fix is to remove the special cases from JVM and CommonJs implementations so they use the standard kotlinx-datetime format parsing, just like the native implementation already does.

Let me implement the fix:

